Just noticed my 1.9.9 light client is affected by this as well, and as others have reported, removing the MultiGeth peer returns the CPU usage to normal.

Here is a little javascript I run on a cron job:

```javascript
// remove-peer.js
var peers = admin.peers;
var dtStr = (new Date()).toLocaleString();

console.log(dtStr + '> ' + peers.length + ' peers');

peers.forEach( function(peer) {
   if (peer.name.indexOf('MultiGeth') != -1 && peer.protocols.les.difficulty < 1.0e+22) {
      console.log(dtStr + '> **** bad node, removing peer:');
      console.log('    ' + peer.name);
      console.log('    ' + peer.enode);
      admin.removePeer(peer.enode);
   }
});
```

Then run it like this :

```
geth --exec 'loadScript("./remove-peer.js")' attach
```

I don't know if the rejection criteria I'm using is the best.  Maybe somebody has something better.
